Problem 1a

For each of the 12 variables, plot the distribution using either a histogram or stem-and-leaf plot, whichever you deem more appropriate (for each variable).

Explanation

Using Stem and leaf plot for integer data type variables while using histogram to visualise continuous numeric variables. Histogram gives better visualization and readibility for continuous variables. Stem and leaf plot works fine when number of categories are less and easier to visualize. Upon increasing more and more classes, it becomes harder to read stem and leaf plot

for (column_name in colnames(df)) {
  unique_count <- length(unique(df[[column_name]]))
  data_type <- class(df[[column_name]])
  cat("Column Name:", column_name, "\n")
  cat("Unique Values Count:", unique_count, "\n")
  cat("Data Type:", data_type, "\n")
  cat("\n")
}

  if (class(df[[column_name]]) == "integer") {
    cat("Stem-and-Leaf Plot for", column_name, ":\n")
    stem(df[[column_name]])
    cat("\n")
  } else {
    #cat("Histogram for", column_name, ":\n")
    hist(df[[column_name]], main = paste("Histogram for", column_name),
         xlab = column_name, ylab = "Frequency", col = "blue", border = "black")
    cat("\n")
  }
}

Problem 1c

For each variable, compute the skewness and kurtotsis. Which variables are skewed left, skewed right, and not significantly skewed? Which are mesokurtic (kurtosis around 3), leptokurtic (kurtosis > 3, fat tails), and platykurtic (kurtosis < 3, thin tails)?

# Install and load the 'e1071' package
if (!requireNamespace("e1071", quietly = TRUE)) {
  install.packages("e1071")
}
library(e1071)

# Function to classify skewness
classify_skewness <- function(skewness_value) {
  if (is.na(skewness_value)) {
    return("Undefined (Missing Value)")
  } else if (abs(skewness_value) < 0.5) {
    return("Not significantly skewed")
  } else if (skewness_value < -0.5) {
    return("Skewed left")
  } else if (skewness_value > 0.5) {
    return("Skewed right")
  } else {
    return("Undefined")
  }
}

# Function to classify kurtosis
classify_kurtosis <- function(kurtosis_value) {
  if (is.na(kurtosis_value)) {
    return("Undefined (Missing Value)")
  } else if (abs(kurtosis_value - 3) < 1) {
    return("Mesokurtic")
  } else if (kurtosis_value > 3) {
    return("Leptokurtic")
  } else if (kurtosis_value < 3) {
    return("Platykurtic")
  } else {
    return("Undefined")
  }
}


# Calculate skewness and kurtosis for each variable, ignoring missing values
skewness_values <- sapply(df, skewness, type = 1)  # Type 1 for Pearson's skewness
kurtosis_values <- sapply(df, kurtosis, type = 1)  # Type 1 for Pearson's kurtosis

# Classify skewness and kurtosis for each variable
skewness_classification <- sapply(skewness_values, classify_skewness)
kurtosis_classification <- sapply(kurtosis_values, classify_kurtosis)

# Print the classification for each variable
for (i in 1:length(skewness_classification)) {
  cat("Variable:", names(skewness_classification)[i], "\n")
  cat("Skewness:", skewness_values[i], "\n")
  cat("Kurtosis:", kurtosis_values[i], "\n")
  cat("Skewness Classification:", skewness_classification[i], "\n")
  cat("Kurtosis Classification:", kurtosis_classification[i], "\n")
  cat("-------------------------------------\n")
}

# Function to create and display Q-Q plots for a given variable
create_and_display_qq_plot <- function(variable, variable_name) {
  # Remove NA values
  variable <- na.omit(variable)
  
  # Create Q-Q plot
  qqnorm(variable)
  qqline(variable)
  
  # Print a message
  cat("Q-Q Plot for Variable:", variable_name, "\n")
  
  # Display the plot (do not save)
  plot.new()
}

# Loop through each variable in the dataframe and create/display Q-Q plots
for (variable_name in colnames(df)) {
  create_and_display_qq_plot(df[, variable_name], variable_name)
}

Problem 2b

Split the dataset into 5-folds. For each fold, use random sampling (from the training set) to fill in the missing values. Train a linear regression model. Compute the Mean Squared Error (MSE), i.e.compute 1 N P N i=1 (yi yi) 2 (where N is s the size of the dataset, yi is the actual wine quality, and yi is the predicted wine quality). Record the average MSE for both the training and test datasets

library(caret)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: lattice
# Load the dataset
redwine_data <- read.table("redwine.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "")

set.seed(1)
num_folds = 5
# Set up repeated k-fold cross-validation
folds <- createFolds(redwine_data$QA, k = num_folds)
# Function to impute missing values, if any
impute_missing_values_with_random <- function(data) {
  for(i in 1:ncol(data)){
    
    na_indices <- which(is.na(data[, i]))
    non_na_indices <- which(!is.na(data[, i]))
    
    data[na_indices, i] <- sample(data[non_na_indices, i], length(na_indices), replace = TRUE)
  }
  return(data)
}

# Custom function to calculate MSE
calculate_mse <- function(actual, predicted) {
  sum((actual - predicted)^2) / length(actual)
}
library(caret)
set.seed(1) # for reproducibility

redwine_data <- read.table("redwine.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "")

# Initialize vectors to store the MSE for each fold
mse_train <- numeric(num_folds)
mse_test <- numeric(num_folds)

# Loop over each fold
for(i in 1:num_folds){
  # Split the data into training and test sets
  curr_fold = folds[[i]]  
  train_data <- redwine_data[-curr_fold, ]
  test_data <- redwine_data[curr_fold, ]
  
  #print(paste("Training Set Size: ", nrow(train_data)))
  #print(paste("Test Set Size: ", nrow(test_data)))

  # Impute Missing Values in the dataset
  train_data <- impute_missing_values_with_random(train_data)
  test_data <- impute_missing_values_with_random(test_data)
  # Train the linear regression model
  model <- lm(QA ~ ., data = train_data)
  
  # Predict on training and test data
  predictions_train <- predict(model, train_data)
  predictions_test <- predict(model, test_data)
    
  # Compute MSE for training and test sets
  mse_train[i] <- calculate_mse(train_data$QA, predictions_train)
  mse_test[i] <- calculate_mse(test_data$QA, predictions_test)
}

# Output the average MSE for both training and test datasets
average_mse_train <- mean(mse_train)
average_mse_test <- mean(mse_test)

print(paste("Average MSE for Training Dataset: ", average_mse_train))
## [1] "Average MSE for Training Dataset:  0.417443866616441"
print(paste("Average MSE for Testing Dataset: ", average_mse_test))
## [1] "Average MSE for Testing Dataset:  0.422877102049628"

Problem 2c

Repeat the process in Problem 2b, using the most common value method to fill missing values. Use the same CV folds.

# Function to calculate the mode (most common value)
calculate_mode <- function(x) {
  # Create a frequency table of the non-NA values
  freq_table <- table(na.omit(x))
  # Return the value (name) of the max frequency (non-NA)
  as.numeric(names(freq_table)[which.max(freq_table)])
}

impute_missing_values_with_mode <- function(data) {
  for(i in 1:ncol(data)){
    # Calculate mode for the current column
    mode_value <- calculate_mode(data[[i]])
    # Replace NA values with the mode value
    data[is.na(data[[i]]), i] <- mode_value
  }
  return(data)
}
library(caret)

  #print(paste("Training Set Size: ", nrow(train_data)))
  #print(paste("Test Set Size: ", nrow(test_data)))

  # Impute Missing Values in the dataset
  train_data <- impute_missing_values_with_mode(train_data)
  test_data <- impute_missing_values_with_mode(test_data)

Problem 2d

Repeat the process in Problem 2b, using the average value method to fill missing values. Use the same CV folds

impute_missing_values_with_mean <- function(data) {
  for(i in 1:ncol(data)){
    # Calculate mean for the current column, excluding NA values
    mean_value <- mean(data[[i]], na.rm = TRUE)
    # Replace NA values with the mean value
    data[is.na(data[[i]]), i] <- mean_value
  }
  return(data)
}
library(caret)

  #print(paste("Training Set Size: ", nrow(train_data)))
  #print(paste("Test Set Size: ", nrow(test_data)))

  # Impute Missing Values in the dataset
  train_data <- impute_missing_values_with_mean(train_data)
  test_data <- impute_missing_values_with_mean(test_data)
  # Train the linear regression model

  #print(paste("Test Set Size: ", nrow(test_data)))

  # Impute Missing Values in the dataset    
  train_data <- complete(mice(train_data, method = 'pmm', m = 1, maxit = 5, seed = 1),1)
  test_data <- complete(mice(test_data, method = 'pmm', m = 1, maxit = 5, seed = 1),1)

  # Train the linear regression model
  model <- lm(QA ~ ., data = train_data)
  
  # Predict on training and test data

  predictions_test <- predict(model, test_data)
    
  # Compute MSE for training and test sets
  mse_train[i] <- calculate_mse(train_data$QA, predictions_train)
  mse_test[i] <- calculate_mse(test_data$QA, predictions_test)
}

Problem 2g

Repeat the process in Problem 2b, omitting samples with missing values. Use the same CV folds.

library(caret)
set.seed(1) # for reproducibility

# Load the dataset
redwine_data <- read.table("redwine.txt", header = TRUE, sep = "")

# Initialize vectors to store the MSE for each fold
mse_train <- numeric(num_folds)
mse_test <- numeric(num_folds)

# Loop over each fold
for(i in 1:num_folds){
  # Split the data into training and test sets
  curr_fold = folds[[i]]  
  train_data <- redwine_data[-curr_fold, ]
  test_data <- redwine_data[curr_fold, ]

  train_data <- na.omit(train_data)
  test_data <- na.omit(test_data)
  # Train the linear regression model
  model <- lm(QA ~ ., data = train_data)
  
  # Predict on training and test data
  predictions_train <- predict(model, train_data)
  predictions_test <- predict(model, test_data)
    
  # Compute MSE for training and test sets
  mse_train[i] <- calculate_mse(train_data$QA, predictions_train)
  mse_test[i] <- calculate_mse(test_data$QA, predictions_test)
}

# Output the average MSE for both training and test datasets
average_mse_train <- mean(mse_train)
average_mse_test <- mean(mse_test)

print(paste("Average MSE for Training Dataset: ", average_mse_train))
## [1] "Average MSE for Training Dataset:  0.420153643581382"
print(paste("Average MSE for Testing Dataset: ", average_mse_test))
## [1] "Average MSE for Testing Dataset:  0.425801604734032"

Problem 2h

Which method for handling missing values performs best? Why may this be?

Explanation

Here all the imputaton techniques have worked quite similarly. There is no major differences in their performances. However Mean imputation has slightly better numbers but they are not very significant. This may be due to less missing values in the data, thats why all the algorithms seems to work more or less similarly
